  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Is Prime Minister of India a constitutional post?",
  "response": "Yes, the position of the **Prime Minister of India** is a constitutional post, even though the title \"Prime Minister\" itself is not explicitly mentioned in the **Constitution of India**. Instead, the role and powers of the Prime Minister are derived from various provisions within the Constitution. Here's a detailed explanation:\n\n### Constitutional Basis\n\n1. **Executive Authority**:\n   - **Article 74** of the Constitution states that there shall be a Council of Ministers with the Prime Minister at its head to aid and advise the President in the exercise of his functions. This establishes the framework for the executive branch of the government.\n\n2. **Council of Ministers**:\n   - **Article 75** elaborates on the appointment and responsibilities of the Council of Ministers. While it doesn't specifically mention the \"Prime Minister,\" it refers to the **\"Minister of the Union\"** who is generally recognized as the Prime Minister in practice.\n   \n3. **Head of Government**:\n   - The Prime Minister is recognized as the **head of government**, responsible for running the country's administration and making policy decisions. This role is established through constitutional conventions and the collective responsibility of the Council of Ministers to the Parliament.\n\n### Constitutional Conventions\n\nWhile the Constitution provides the structural framework, many aspects of the Prime Minister's role are governed by established **constitutional conventions**:\n\n- **Leader of the Majority Party**: Typically, the Prime Minister is the leader of the party (or coalition) that has a majority in the **Lok Sabha** (the lower house of Parliament).\n- **Prime Minister as Chief Advisor**: The President of India acts on the advice of the Prime Minister and the Council of Ministers in most matters.\n- **Duties and Powers**: The Prime Minister coordinates and supervises the functioning of various ministries and plays a pivotal role in legislative affairs.\n\n### Judicial Interpretations\n\nIndian courts have recognized the Prime Minister's role through various judgments, reinforcing the constitutional validity of the position and its importance in the governance structure.\n\n### Summary\n\nWhile the title \"Prime Minister\" isn't directly mentioned in the Constitution, the role is inherently constitutional, derived from the provisions related to the executive branch, the Council of Ministers, and the principles of parliamentary democracy outlined in the Constitution of India. The position's existence and functions are upheld by constitutional provisions, conventions, and judicial interpretations, making it a fundamental constitutional post in India's governance framework.",
